1. Networking Basics

Imagine your home network:

Internet
    │
    ▼
Router (192.168.1.1)
    │
 ┌──┴─────────────┐
 │                │
Laptop        Mobile
192.168.1.10 192.168.1.20

Every device has an IP address, which acts like its house number on the network.

Types of IP Addresses
Private IP: Used inside your local network (e.g., 192.168.x.x, 10.x.x.x, 172.16.x.x).
Public IP: Used on the internet and assigned by your ISP or cloud provider.
2. Check Your IP Address

Modern Linux uses the ip command.

ip addr

Short version:

ip a

Look for output like:

inet 192.168.1.10/24

This is your machine's IP address.

3. Check Network Interfaces
ip link

Typical interfaces:

Interface	Purpose
lo	Loopback (127.0.0.1)
eth0	Ethernet
ens33	VMware
enp0s3	VirtualBox
wlan0	Wi-Fi
4. View Routing Table
ip route

Example:

default via 192.168.1.1 dev enp0s3
192.168.1.0/24 dev enp0s3

The default gateway is where traffic goes if Linux doesn't know a more specific route.

5. Test Connectivity with ping

Ping your router:

ping 192.168.1.1

Ping Google DNS:

ping 8.8.8.8

Ping a website:

ping google.com
How to Interpret Results
ping 8.8.8.8 works, but ping google.com fails → Likely a DNS issue.
Both fail → Likely a network connectivity issue.

Stop ping with Ctrl + C.

6. Check DNS Resolution

DNS converts domain names into IP addresses.

Use:

nslookup google.com

or

dig google.com

If dig isn't installed:

sudo apt install dnsutils
7. Test HTTP Requests with curl

Check if a website responds:

curl https://google.com

Only fetch headers:

curl -I https://google.com

This is very useful for testing APIs and web servers.

8. Download Files with wget
wget https://example.com/file.zip

wget is often used in automation scripts.

9. Check Open Ports

Modern command:

ss -tuln

Options:

t → TCP
u → UDP
l → Listening sockets
n → Numeric addresses

Example:

tcp LISTEN 0 511 0.0.0.0:22

This means SSH is listening on port 22.

10. Find Which Process Uses a Port

Example for port 80:

sudo ss -tulpn | grep :80

This helps identify which service is using a specific port.

11. Check Listening Services
sudo ss -tulpn

Pay attention to:

Port
Process name
PID
12. Test Specific Ports

If nc (Netcat) is installed:

nc -zv google.com 443

This checks whether port 443 is reachable.

13. View Hostname
hostname

View detailed host information:

hostnamectl

Change hostname (requires reboot or restart of relevant services to fully propagate):

sudo hostnamectl set-hostname devops-server
14. View DNS Configuration
cat /etc/resolv.conf

Typical output:

nameserver 8.8.8.8
15. Useful Networking Commands
Command	Purpose
ip a	Show IP addresses
ip route	Show routing table
ping	Test connectivity
curl	Test HTTP/HTTPS
wget	Download files
ss -tulpn	Show listening ports
hostnamectl	Show hostname info
nslookup	DNS lookup
dig	Advanced DNS lookup
nc	Test TCP/UDP connectivity
