🎤 Interview Questions
What is the difference between a private IP and a public IP?
Private IP	                                                Public IP
Used within a local network (LAN).                      	Used on the internet.
Not directly reachable from the internet.	                Globally unique and reachable on the internet.
Assigned by a router or local network.	                    Assigned by an ISP or cloud provider.
Private IP ranges (IPv4):
10.0.0.0/8
172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255
192.168.0.0/16
Example:
Private IP: 192.168.1.10
Public IP: 203.0.113.25



What does ip a display?
ip a (or ip addr) displays:

Network interfaces
IPv4 and IPv6 addresses
Interface state (UP/DOWN)
MAC addresses
MTU information

What is the purpose of the routing table?
The routing table tells the operating system where to send network packets. It determines the next hop (gateway) or interface for traffic destined to different networks.
View it with:
ip route
Example output:
default via 192.168.1.1 dev eth0
192.168.1.0/24 dev eth0 proto kernel

What is DNS?
DNS (Domain Name System) translates domain names into IP addresses.
Example:
google.com → 142.250.x.x
Without DNS, users would have to remember IP addresses instead of domain names.

What is the difference between ping and curl?
Ping	                                      curl
Tests network connectivity using ICMP.	      Sends requests to HTTP, HTTPS, FTP, and other protocols.
Checks if a host is reachable.	              Retrieves data from a server or API.
Does not test web application responses.	  Can test websites, APIs, headers, authentication, and more.
Examples:
ping google.com
curl https://example.com

What does ss -tulpn show?
ss -tulpn
Displays:
TCP (-t) and UDP (-u) sockets
Listening ports (-l)
Numeric addresses (-n)
Processes using the sockets (-p)
It's commonly used to verify which services are listening on which ports.

How do you identify the process listening on a specific port?
Using ss:
sudo ss -tulpn | grep :80
Example output:
tcp LISTEN ... users:(("nginx",pid=1234))
This shows that nginx is listening on port 80.

What does curl -I do?
curl -I sends an HTTP HEAD request and returns only the response headers, not the response body.
Example:
curl -I https://example.com
Typical output:
HTTP/2 200
content-type: text/html
server: nginx
This is useful for checking:
HTTP status codes
Response headers
Server information
Redirects

What is the purpose of /etc/resolv.conf?
/etc/resolv.conf contains the DNS resolver configuration, including the DNS servers the system should use.
Example:
nameserver 8.8.8.8
nameserver 1.1.1.1
View it with:
cat /etc/resolv.conf

If ping 8.8.8.8 succeeds but ping google.com fails, what is the likely issue?
The most likely issue is DNS resolution.
Reason:
ping 8.8.8.8 uses an IP address directly, so it does not require DNS.
ping google.com requires the system to resolve the domain name to an IP address.
Things to check:
/etc/resolv.conf
DNS server availability
systemd-resolved (if used)

Quick Interview Revision
Private IP: Used inside local networks; not internet-routable.
Public IP: Globally routable internet address.
ip a: Shows network interfaces, IP addresses, and interface status.
Routing table: Determines how packets reach their destination.
DNS: Converts domain names into IP addresses.
ping: Tests basic network reachability using ICMP.
curl: Sends HTTP/HTTPS (and other protocol) requests to servers.
ss -tulpn: Displays listening TCP/UDP ports and the associated processes.
Identify a process on a port: sudo ss -tulpn | grep :<port>.
curl -I: Retrieves only HTTP response headers.
/etc/resolv.conf: Stores DNS resolver configuration.
ping 8.8.8.8 works but ping google.com fails: Indicates a DNS resolution problem.



